\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section,
 we study the extent to which costs of payments are passed though to retail prices and thus to firm sales.
 Our prior results show large differences in the payment mix and associated interchange fees,
 both within and across payment methods.
 These results suggest that payments result in cross-subsidization between parties in the payment system.
 If payment costs are fully passed though by merchants,
 then consumers of payments with low interchange fees subsidize consumers with premium payment methods.
 Alternatively,
 if merchants do not pass through interchange fees into retail prices,
 then cross-subsidization between cash and card users does not occur;
 instead,
 merchants effectively bear the burden of subsidizing card rewards themselves.
 Using our detailed merchant-level data,
 we exploit heterogeneity in the impact of the Durbin Amendment across merchants to show that interchange fees affect the allocation of consumption and retail prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential Impact of the Durbin Amendment 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 2011 Durbin Amendment,
 passed as part of the Dodd–Frank Act,
 imposed a binding cap on debit card interchange fees for banks with over $10 billion in assets.
 It limited fees to a maximum of 22 cents plus 0.05% of the transaction amount.
 The rule applied only debit cards issued by large banks (regulated debit) and left fees for debit cards issued by small banks and credit unions unchanged (exempt debit).
 As illustrated in Figure 
