\begin_layout Subsection
Pass-though estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate the pass-though of interchange fee to prices and the resulting change in sales exploiting the variation induced by the Durbin Amendment.
 Because interchange fees depend on merchant characteristics,
 which are themselves related to sales we use a simulated IV approach:
 we construct fee changes each merchant would face,
 based only on their pre-policy characteristics and the regulated post-Durbin schedule.
 Formally,
 we estimate the impact of interchange on sales and prices using the following following specification using the restaurant industry,
 which faced the largest variation in fees following the regulatory change:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta y_{j}=\beta\Delta\tau_{j}+\epsilon_{j}\label{eq:durbin}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The dependent variable,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta y_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 is the change in sales or prices at merchant 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in the year following the implementation of the Durbin Amendment (i.e.,
 October 2011 to October 2012).
 The independent variable of interest,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 measures the average change in credit and debit interchange fees at the merchant over the same period.
 Observations are at the merchant level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As discussed in Section 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ref{sec:costs}
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 interchange fees depend on merchant characteristics,
 including sales volume and average transaction size.
 For example,
 if the firms with the fastest sales growth are also the ones that expand the debit card share of sales or increase average transaction sizes,
 that would mechanically generate a negative correlation between lower interchange fees and stronger sales growth.
 The fact that most of the variation in interchange fees stems from the Durbin Amendment,
 an arguably exogenous policy shock,
 helps alleviate these concerns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address the potential endogeneity issue,
 we construct an instrument based on the expected decline in interchange fees resulting from the Durbin Amendment,
 derived from each merchant’s pre-policy characteristics.
 We calculate the expected change in interchange fees as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\Delta\tau_{j}}=r_{z(j)}\times d_{j}\times\left(\tau^{\text{Reg Debit,Post}}(t_{j})-\tau^{\text{Debit,Pre}}(t_{j})\right)
\]

\end_inset

Here,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{z(j)}$
\end_inset

 is the share of debit cards in merchant 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

's zip code that are subject to Durbin regulation;
 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the share of the merchant’s card sales made with debit cards in the pre-Durbin period;
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the merchant’s average transaction size in the pre-Durbin period.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{\text{RegDebit,Post}}(t_{j})$
\end_inset

 is the expected interchange rate under the post-Durbin regulated debit fee schedule,
 given transaction size 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{j}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{\text{Debit,Pre}}(t_{j})$
\end_inset

 is the expected rate under the pre-Durbin fee schedule for the same 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 This instrument captures the theoretical savings for a merchant,
 assuming no change in transaction size or payment composition after the policy.
 It exploits heterogeneity in both the expected share of regulated debit transactions and the change in regulated-debit interchange fees.
\end_layout

