\begin_layout Subsection
Sufficient Statistic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We derive the sufficient statistic,
 which captures the money-metric welfare effects of changes in interchange rates.
 The intuition behind our result builds on Roy's identity:
 even though interchange fees can affect how consumers allocate their consumption across merchants,
 this margin of adjustment does not have a direct effects on consumer welfare.
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{k}\left(p,f_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 as the indirect utility function from this consumer problem,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{k}$
\end_inset

 be the Lagrange multiplier on the budget constraint.
 By Roy's identity,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The regularity assumptions (WHICH) ensure a unique interior optimal choice of consumption for every price vector 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

,
 and thus we can use Roy's identity .
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial V_{k}}{\partial p_{j}}=-q_{jk}^{*}\times\lambda_{k}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{jk}^{*}$
\end_inset

 reflects consumption at the optimum.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in how changes in interchange fees affect consumer welfare.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}$
\end_inset

 be any parameter that affects the fees on payment method 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 (NEED EXAMPLE).
 We would like to compute the money-metric effect of changing 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{l}$
\end_inset

 on the welfare of consumers who use payment method 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 By applying Roy's identity and dropping all higher order terms in 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

,
 we obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{\lambda_{k}}\frac{dV_{k}}{dx_{l}} & =\sum_{j}-q_{jk}^{*}\frac{\partial p_{j}}{\partial x_{l}}+\frac{\partial f_{k}}{\partial x_{l}}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{j}-q_{jk}^{*}p_{j}\left(\mu_{jl}\frac{\partial\tau_{jl}}{\partial x_{l}}+\frac{\partial\mu_{jl}}{\partial x_{l}}\tau_{jl}\right)+\frac{\partial f_{k}}{\partial x_{l}}\nonumber \\
 & \approx\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\right]^{-1}\left(-\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}\frac{\partial\tau_{jl}}{\partial x_{l}}\right]+I\left\{ k=l\right\} \times\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\frac{\partial\tau_{jk}}{\partial x_{k}}\right]\right)\label{eq:sufficient-stat-formula}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above expression captures the money-metric effect on a representative consumer of payment method 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 To convert to dollar values,
 we multiply equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sufficient-stat-formula"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\right]$
\end_inset

,
 the total amount of spending by payment method 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 consumers and the dollar amount of spending across all payment methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Applying the Sufficient Statistic to Changes in the Interchange Fee Schedule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our sufficient statistic provides intuition on the effects of changing the overall level of fees and reducing fee heterogeneity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Baseline Fees
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model changing the baseline fee by perturbing 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\tau}_{l}$
\end_inset

 (WHAT IS THIS).
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\tau_{jl}}{\partial\overline{\tau}_{l}}=1$
\end_inset

,
 the re-distributive effect of reducing the baseline interchange level by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 in dollar terms for all consumers who use payment method 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\times\left(\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}\right]-I\left\{ k=l\right\} \mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\right]\right)\label{eq:baseline-effect}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This first term of the formula says that a decrease in the overall fees on card 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 benefits consumers of card 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 by lowering retail prices by the extent to which card 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and card 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 consumers overlap.
 The second term then says that card 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 consumers are hurt from lowering fees on card 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 because they receive fewer rewards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The appearance of second moments makes the framework rich enough to nest leading cases in the literature.
 When consumers with different cards shop at disjoint sets of merchants,
 as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gans2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq l$
\end_inset

 and there is no redistribution.
 Conversely,
 when merchants are homogeneous,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{jk}=\overline{\mu}_{k}$
\end_inset

 for all merchants 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
 the redistribution depends on the aggregate share of each card type,
 consistent with the intuition in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Felt.etal2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To the extent that there is a large mass of cash-only merchants that are both unobserved in our dataset and not well captured in the GDP statistics,
 the second moments are zero and thus ignoring them has no effect on our estimates of redistribution.
 Thus,
 the sufficient-statistics framework captures a wide range of economic environments—
from perfect merchant homogeneity to full segmentation—
allowing us to quantify redistribution in the presence of observed heterogeneity in payment behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Sector Discounts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model eliminating the sector discounts by perturbing 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{rl}$
\end_inset

.
 The dollar effect of removing all of the sector level discounts on card 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{r}\tau_{rl}\times\frac{\partial V_{k}}{\partial\tau_{rl}} & =\sum_{r}\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}I\left\{ s_{j}=r\right\} \right]\tau_{rl}-I\left\{ k=l\right\} \mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\tau_{rk}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{r}\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}\rvert s_{j}=r\right]P_{R}\left(s_{j}=r\right)\tau_{rl}\label{eq:sector-effect}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{jk}\tau_{rk}$
\end_inset

 terms sum to zero from the normalization of the sector level discounts in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:interchange-fee-model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula says that the sector weighted discounts are transmitted sector-by-sector according to how much consumers overlap in each sector.
 Intuitively,
 if debit card and credit card consumers overlap more in groceries than in travel,
 then a discount for groceries and a higher fee for travel benefits debit card users at the cost of credit card users.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Negotiated Rates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model bargaining by simultaneously removing the bargaining parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{l}$
\end_inset

 while increasing the baseline fee 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\tau}_{l}$
\end_inset

 so as to maintain the same overall level of fees on card 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

.
 In effect,
 we model a removal of price discrimination along the firm size dimension.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We start with the derivative with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{l}$
\end_inset

,
 which yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\tau_{jl}}{\partial\delta_{l}}=b_{j}
\]

\end_inset

Thus the re-distributive effect of a small change in 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{l}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial V_{k}}{\partial\delta_{l}}=-\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}b_{j}\right]+I\left\{ k=l\right\} \times\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jl}b_{j}\right]
\]

\end_inset

To offset the overall change in fees from increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{l}$
\end_inset

,
 we decrease the overall fee 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\tau}_{l}$
\end_inset

 to compensate.
 The amount that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\tau}_{l}$
\end_inset

 needs to increase per increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{l}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jl}b_{j}\right]}{\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jl}\right]}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
\end_layout

\end_inset

The dollar effect of eliminating 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{l}$
\end_inset

 while increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\tau}_{l}$
\end_inset

 to compensate is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & -\delta_{l}\times\left(\frac{\partial V_{k}}{\partial\delta_{l}}-\frac{\partial V_{k}}{\partial\overline{\tau}_{l}}\times\frac{\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jl}b_{j}\right]}{\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jl}\right]}\right)\nonumber \\
= & \delta_{l}P_{R}\left(b_{j}\right)\left(\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}\rvert b_{j}=1\right]-\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}\right]\times\frac{\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jl}\rvert b_{j}=1\right]}{\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jl}\right]}\right)\label{eq:bargain-effect}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formula predicts that debit card users benefit from the discounts that large merchants receive on credit card interchange provided that debit and credit card users overlap more at the merchants that receive discounts than at the merchants that do not.
 To see this,
 consider the case when bargaining and non-bargaining firms have the same average use of payment method 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jl}\rvert b_{j}=1\right]}{\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jl}\right]}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then if 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{l}<0$
\end_inset

,
 consumers on card 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 benefit from the discount (i.e.
 are hurt if the discount is removed) provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}\rvert b_{j}=1\right]>\mathbb{E}_{R}\left[\mu_{jk}\mu_{jl}\rvert b_{j}=0\right]$
\end_inset

.
 This condition holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 users overlap more with 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 users at the large stores with discounted interchange than at the small stores that do not have discounted interchange.
 Because large merchants have a consumer base that covers consumers with different income levels,
 this condition will generally be satisfied,
 highlighting a progressive role for negotiated rates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Comments on the Sufficient Statistic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sufficient statistic formula 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sufficient-stat-formula"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 shows that the redistributive effects of interchange fees can be summarized by the distribution of of payment shares 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 across merchants provided two conditions hold:
 full merchant passthrough to retail prices and full issuer passthrough to rewards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sufficient statistic is valid even when consumers are allowed to re-optimize their consumption in response to retail prices or consumer rewards.
 One intuitive way of evaluating the effects of reducing interchange fees would be to conduct an accounting exercise in which one adjusts retail prices at each store according to the weighted change in interchange fees,
 and then take the expenditure share-weighted sum of these price changes to compute welfare.
 The formula in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sufficient-stat-formula"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 provides a numerically convenient way of doing this exercise.
 One concern with such an exercise is that it omits the result of consumers responding to the change in retail prices by changing their shopping behavior.
 The envelope theorem and Roy's identity highlight that such concerns are second order in the change in interchange fees 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The validity of the sufficient statistic does not depend on any particular value of merchant demand elasticity.
 The essential ingredient comes from the passthrough of interchange fees to retail prices.
 The best empirical evidence that suggests interchange fees should be largely passed through comes from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Amiti.etal2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 who show that sector-level cost shocks are fully passed through,
 whereas idiosyncratic cost shocks are only passed through incompletely at large firms.
 Given that interchange fees affect the cost of all merchants,
 the usual evidence of incomplete passthrough that typically applies to one firm at a time does not apply to the effects of interchange.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the framework treats rewards as being paid out as a lump-sum,
 this is not essential to the argument.
 If rewards were paid out for specific merchants or sectors,
 then taking away rewards would change consumers' allocation of spending across merchants.
 But by Roy's identity,
 the re-optimization across merchants is second-order for welfare.
 Only the income effect while holding fixed consumers' consumption decisions is directly relevant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Counterfactual:
 Quantifying Redistribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We utilize our general formulas to examine the welfare effects of setting interchange fees to zero,
 enabling us to understand the distributional impact of interchange fees across different consumer payment types.
 We apply our framework to a cross-section of sales and interchange fees by card type in 2022.
 To implement our sufficient statistics framework,
 we simply need to know,
 at the merchant level,
 equilibrium payment shares and the corresponding interchange fees,
 both of which are directly observable in our data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Eliminating Interchange Fees and Card Rewards
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:eliminate-interchange"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eliminating interchange fees and card rewards has two equal and opposite effects on consumers as a whole.
 On one hand,
 when interchange fees are set to zero,
 consumers no longer receive rewards when they pay with debit or credit cards.
 On the other hand,
 eliminating interchange fees reduces merchants’ transaction costs,
 which leads to lower prices,
 benefiting all consumers.
 Although these effects offset each other in the aggregate,
 they have large distributional effects.
 Consumers who use high-reward,
 and therefore high-interchange credit cards,
 are worse off,
 whereas consumers who use low-fee payment methods like cash and regulated debit cards are better off.
 Moreover,
 the consumers who use low-fee payment methods at stores that primarily serve other consumers that use high-fee payment methods experience the largest benefits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We compute the consumer welfare effects of setting interchange fees to zero after accounting for consumer sorting and merchant fee heterogeneity in Table 
