\begin_layout Subsubsection
Implications of Merchant Heterogeneity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our sufficient statistics framework shows that the sorting of consumers with different payment preferences across merchants,
 along with fee heterogeneity across merchants shapes the impact of interchange fees on consumers.
 We find that accounting for merchant heterogeneity has important implications for two reasons.
 First,
 as documented in Section
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 
\backslash
ref{sec:costs}
\end_layout

\end_inset

,
 we find evidence of consumer sorting:
 cash,
 debit card,
 and credit card users tend to shop at different merchants,
 which limits cross-subsidization.
 Second,
 the merchants frequented by all consumer types,
 where the potential for redistribution is the greatest,
 tend to pay the lowest interchange fees,
 which inherently restricts redistribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To evaluate the relative importance of these channels,
 it is useful to compare our model's results to a counterfactual model that instead assumes all merchants serve the same mix of consumers,
 and that all cards of a given card type charge all merchants the same fee.
 The second row of Table 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ref{tab:redist}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shows the results under these two assumptions about merchant homogeneity.
 If all merchants were homogeneous,
 the gains to cash users and regulated debit card users from setting interchange fees to zero would be substantially higher.
 Consumer surplus among cash users would increase by 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{combined_cash_naive}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 basis points (approximately $
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{combined_dollar_cash_naive}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 billion).
 Similarly,
 surplus among premium credit card users would decrease by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{combined_premium_credit_naive}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 basis points (roughly $
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{combined_dollar_cash_naive}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 billion).
 In a world of homogenous merchants,
 the losses for premium card users would be 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
$
\backslash
absinput{combined_dollar_premium_credit_overstate}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 larger ,
 and the gains for cash users would be 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
$
\backslash
absinput{combined_dollar_cash_overstate}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 billion larger.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consumer sorting explains most of the difference between our baseline results and the homogeneous-merchant counterfactual.
 Specifically,
 merchant heterogeneity,
 arising from both consumer sorting and interchange fee variation,
 reduces credit card (basic and premium) surplus by roughly $9 billion relative to the homogeneous world.
 Of this,
 about $8 billion is explained by consumer sorting:
 because cardholders disproportionately shop at card-accepting merchants,
 they effectively fund a large share of their own rewards through higher prices.
 The remaining $1 billion comes from interchange fee heterogeneity:
 merchants where cash,
 debit,
 and credit card users all shop—
and where redistribution could be greatest—
tend to pay lower interchange fees,
 further limiting redistribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Merchant heterogeneity,
 therefore,
 has important implications for who pays for rewards.
 The purple triangles in Figure
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

 
\backslash
ref{fig:scatter_interchange}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 show the share of card interchange fees paid by each user group if all merchants were homogeneous.
 This figure illustrates that cross-subsidization would be substantially larger in a setting without merchant heterogeneity.
 For example,
 premium credit card users would still receive 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{premium_credit_rewards}
\end_layout

\end_inset

% of rewards,
 but they would pay for only 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{premium_credit_fees_homogenous_merchants}
\end_layout

\end_inset

% of them.
 In other words,
 the degree of cross-subsidization for credit card rewards would be much greater if there were no consumer sorting across merchants (i.e.,
 if all merchants were homogeneous).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results indicate that premium credit card users would effectively receive 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{premium_share_paid_homog}
\end_layout

\end_inset

% (=(
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{premium_credit_rewards}
\end_layout

\end_inset

%-
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{premium_credit_fees_homogenous_merchants}
\end_layout

\end_inset

%)/
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{premium_credit_rewards}
\end_layout

\end_inset

%) of their rewards for free if merchants were homogeneous.
 However,
 due to consumer sorting across merchants by payment method,
 premium credit card users currently receive only 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{premium_share_paid_final}
\end_layout

\end_inset

% (=(
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
scalarinput{premium_credit_rewards}
\end_layout

\end_inset

%-
\begin_inset ERT
